      <h2>Key People in Gaskell’s Journal</h2>
      <h3>Individuals Referenced in the Journal:</h3>
      
      
      <div class="persRef" id="MA_Gaskell_Holland">
         
         <h4><span class="forename">Marianne</span><span class="givenName">Gaskell</span><span class="marriedName">Holland</span></h4>
         <h4>Born September 12 1834</h4>
         <h4>Died </h4>
         <h4>Bio: </h4>
         <p>
            The Gaskells’ first surviving daughter, Marianne, born September 12, 1834. Marianne, often called "M.A." or simply "MA" by Gaskell, is the subject of most
            of the journal,
            and is described as gentle. She was the only one of Gaskell’s
            daughters to become a mother herself, though she was still unmarried at the
            time of Gaskell’s death. The journal has been passed down through Marianne's descendants.The Gaskells’ first surviving daughter, Marianne, born September 12, 1834September 12, 1834. Marianne, often called "M.A." or simply "MA" by Gaskell, is the subject of most
            of the journal,
            and is described as gentlegentle. She was the only one of Gaskell’s
            daughters to become a mother herself, though she was still unmarried at the
            time of Gaskell’s death. The journal has been passed down through Marianne's descendants.
            </p>
         
         September 12 1834Manchester, UK/&gt; 
         
         
         
         
         
         The Gaskells’ first surviving daughter, Marianne, born September 12, 1834. Marianne, often called "M.A." or simply "MA" by Gaskell, is the subject of most
         of the journal,
         and is described as gentle. She was the only one of Gaskell’s
         daughters to become a mother herself, though she was still unmarried at the
         time of Gaskell’s death. The journal has been passed down through Marianne's descendants.
         
         </div>
      
      <div class="persRef" id="Wm_Gaskell">
         
         <h4><span class="forename">William</span><span class="givenName">Gaskell</span><span class="marriedName"></span></h4>
         <h4>Born July 24, 1805</h4>
         <h4>Died </h4>
         <h4>Bio: </h4>
         <p>
            Elizabeth Gaskell’s husband, a Unitarian minister. They married August 30,
            1832. At the time, William was serving at the Cross Street Chapel,
            Manchester, with J. G. Robberds. Elizabeth Gaskell’s husband, a Unitarian minister. They married August 30,
            1832. At the time, William was serving at the Cross Street Chapel,
            Manchester, with J. G. Robberds. 
            </p>
         July 24, 1805
         Latchford, Warrington, UK
         
         
         Manchester, UK
         
         
         Elizabeth Gaskell’s husband, a Unitarian minister. They married August 30,
         1832. At the time, William was serving at the Cross Street Chapel,
         Manchester, with J. G. Robberds. 
         
         </div>
      
      <div class="persRef" id="Mme_DeSaussure">
         
         <h4><span class="forename">Albertine</span><span class="givenName">Necker</span><span class="marriedName">de Saussure</span></h4>
         <h4>Born </h4>
         <h4>Died </h4>
         <h4>Bio: </h4>
         <p>
            Albertine Necker de Saussure was a Swiss woman of letters, most well known
            for her L’Education progressive. She was related through her botanist
            husband to Germaine de Staël.Albertine Necker de Saussure was a Swiss woman of letters, most well known
            for her L’Education progressiveL’Education progressive. She was related through her botanist
            husband to Germaine de Staël.
            </p>
         
         
         
         
         
         
         
         Albertine Necker de Saussure was a Swiss woman of letters, most well known
         for her L’Education progressive. She was related through her botanist
         husband to Germaine de Staël.
         
         </div>
      
      <div class="persRef" id="Andrew_Combe">
         
         <h4><span class="forename">Andrew</span><span class="givenName">Combe</span><span class="marriedName"></span></h4>
         <h4>Born </h4>
         <h4>Died </h4>
         <h4>Bio: </h4>
         <p>Author, scientist. Combe was a
            Physician/Phrenologist, who established the Phrenological
            Journal with his brother and others. He was also the President of
            Edinburgh Phrenological Society in 1827. Gaskell
            quotes his Physiology applied to Health and
            Education (1834), which was a bestseller. Author, scientist. Combe was a
            Physician/Phrenologist, who established the Phrenological
            JournalPhrenological
